name.text: 15.2.2.4 y coord of COM of lamina by vertical strips

questiontext.text:
Exercise

In this exercise we use the same tall and narrow rectangles as in the previous exercise, but we now consider the moment about the \(x\)-axis in order to find \(\bar{y}\).  

  1. Referring to the figure again, the centre of mass of the rectangular slice must lie half way along its length, that is, its \(y\)-coordinate is \(\dfrac{y}{2}=\dfrac{x}{2}\). Assume that all the mass of the slice, \(x \rho \delta x\), acts at this point, the moment about the \(x\)-axis is:
    [[input:ans0]][[validation:ans0]] [[feedback:prt0]]
    Enter rho for \(\rho\).


  2. Adding contributions from all slices gives the sum and letting \(\delta x \to 0\) we obtain the integral:

    \( \displaystyle{\int_{x=0}^{2}}\) [[input:ans1]]\(\textrm{d}x\) [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]

  3. Evaluate the above integral.

    [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]

  4. Similar to the previous exercise the moment of the total mass about the \(x\)-axis is \(2 \rho \bar{y}\). Setting this equal to the value in part (c) determine \(\bar{y}\).

    \(\bar{y}=\)[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]

generalfeedback.text:
1. \(\displaystyle {@ta0@}\)

  2. \(\displaystyle \int_{x=0}^{2} \frac{\rho y^2}{2} \textrm{d}x\)

  3. \({4 \rho}{3}\)

  4. \(2 \rho \bar{y} = \dfrac{4 \rho}{3} \) from which \(\bar{y} = \dfrac{2}{3}\). The coordinates of the centre of mass are \((\frac{4}{3}, \frac{2}{3})\).
